TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rivalry Between Multinational Enterprises: An Event History Approach
AU  - Yu, Tieying
AU  - Cannella, Albert A.
Y1  - 2007/06/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.25527425
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.25527425
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 665
EP  - 686
VL  - 50
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Our study investigates rivalry between multinational enterprises (MNEs) in host country markets. Drawing on the awareness-motivation-capability perspective, we show how the speed of an MNE's response to a rival's attack is influenced by resource-related factors, including distance, government constraints, and subsidiary control, and by market-related factors, including initiating country importance, location of the response in the initiating country, and multimarket contact. We provide a new conceptualization and empirical approach for studying rivalry between MNEs. Additionally, our theory and evidence imply that important constraints on MNE actions in host country markets go well beyond the constraints faced in domestic competition.
AB  - Our study investigates rivalry between multinational enterprises (MNEs) in host country markets. Drawing on the awareness-motivation-capability perspective, we show how the speed of an MNE's response to a rival's attack is influenced by resource-related factors, including distance, government constraints, and subsidiary control, and by market-related factors, including initiating country importance, location of the response in the initiating country, and multimarket contact. We provide a new conceptualization and empirical approach for studying rivalry between MNEs. Additionally, our theory and evidence imply that important constraints on MNE actions in host country markets go well beyond the constraints faced in domestic competition.
